# Next.js + LangChain Project Standards

## 1. STACK AND VERSION ALIGNMENT

- Follow patterns compatible with this project stack:
  - Next.js 16 (App Router)
  - React 19
  - TypeScript 5
  - ESLint 9
- Do not introduce APIs or patterns removed/deprecated for these versions.

## 2. ARCHITECTURE RULES

- Use App Router structure under `src/app`.
- Keep server-side LLM and retrieval logic in API routes or server modules only.
- Never expose API secrets or provider keys to client components.
- Keep UI components focused on rendering and interaction; move business logic to `src/lib`.

## 3. RECOMMENDED FOLDER STRUCTURE

- `src/app/api/chat/route.ts` for chat request handling.
- `src/lib/llm/` for model configuration and wrappers.
- `src/lib/rag/` for document loading, chunking, embeddings, and retrieval.
- `src/lib/tools/` for tool definitions and schemas.
- `src/types/` for shared TypeScript types when needed.
- `data/` for local knowledge-base files used by RAG.

## 4. RAG IMPLEMENTATION STANDARDS

- Use typed document processing and retrieval pipelines.
- Keep chunking configuration explicit and centralized.
- Return source metadata with answers when possible.
- Add input validation and graceful error handling for retrieval failures.
- Log retrieval and tool-call steps in a privacy-safe way (no secret leakage).

## 5. TOOL CALLING STANDARDS

- Implement at least 3 domain-relevant tools.
- Validate tool inputs with a schema library (for example `zod`).
- Keep each tool in a separate module with a clear single responsibility.
- Ensure tool execution errors return safe, user-friendly messages.

## 6. API ROUTE STANDARDS

- Validate and sanitize incoming request payloads.
- Return typed JSON responses with clear error shapes.
- Use proper HTTP status codes for validation, rate-limit, and server errors.
- Keep route handlers small; delegate logic to `src/lib`.

## 7. SECURITY AND CONFIGURATION

- Read secrets from `.env.local` only on the server.
- Never hardcode API keys, tokens, or private endpoints.
- Add basic rate limiting and input length controls for chat endpoints.
- Avoid logging full user-sensitive content unless explicitly required.

## 8. UI/UX REQUIREMENTS FOR THIS PROJECT

- Show response loading/progress states.
- Display source context and citations when available.
- Display tool-call results in a clear, separate section.
- Keep UI responsive and accessible (labels, keyboard focus, semantic elements).

## 9. CHANGE DISCIPLINE

- Make minimal, task-focused changes only.
- Do not refactor unrelated code unless required for correctness.
- Before finishing work, run lint/type checks and fix newly introduced issues.
